## **1) Have any data been collected for this study already?**

Yes, the current study mostly replicates a preliminary study,
(unpublished; preregistration #129382) whose results matched its
predictions very closely. Due to the undue length of the preliminary
study, we broke it into two separate studies, one of which we are now
preregistering. This version also includes minor changes to increase
conceptual clarity. Specific changes include:

-   We dropped several measures (all of secondary importance)

-   We added new measures to expand the potential theoretical
    contribution

-   We included three alternative vignettes to enhance generalizability
    of the sentencing decision

-   We removed pre/post vignette emotion and Righteousness measures as
    preliminary data showed no differences

-   We also removed a manipulation of the victim's race (Black v.
    White), as preliminary data showed no differences

Other than that, the current predictions are very similar to the ones we
originally preregistered, and we expect the results of this new study to
be very similar to both the predictions and findings made at that
preliminary phase.

## **2) What's the main question being asked or hypothesis being tested in this study?**

We seek to ascertain whether public punitiveness is positively
correlated with a variety of dependent measures (listed in section 3).
From a normative point of view, these factors should be correlated
negatively (or not at all) with punitiveness, especially in light of the
prosocial tenet that underlies the canonic justifications of criminal
punishment (retribution, deterrence, incapacitation, rehabilitation,
norm expression). Positive relationships with punitiveness will call
into question the bedrock tenet of prosocial nature of criminal
punishment.

*Primary Hypotheses:*

**H1:** Punitiveness will be positively correlated with all listed
correlate measures.

**H2:** The \"Hostile Aggression\" cluster (hatred, revenge,
degradation, suffering, prison violence) will show stronger correlations
with punitiveness than the \"Crime Concerns\" cluster (perceived crime
rates, fear of crime).

**H3:** Most correlate measures will be positively intercorrelated,
suggesting a cohesive psychological "punitiveness mindset."

The punitiveness construct will be comprised of the following measures:

-   Belief in more punishment

-   The Benthamite principle of parsimony

-   Support for three strike laws

-   Support for life in prison without the possibility of parole

-   Support for the death penalty

-   A sentencing decision in a second-degree murder case

